Headlines.Author: Joseph Walker
Headlines.Headline: Life Technologies Loses Genetic Sequencing Pioneer Rothberg

PARAGRAPH.#text: Jonathan Rothberg, chief executive of Life Technologies Corp.'s LIFE next-generation genetic sequencing, has resigned, the company said in a regulatory filing Wednesday. Mr. Rothberg's resignation comes as Life aims to complete a $13.6 billion merger with Thermo Fisher Scientific Inc. TMO. Dollar mixed, Treasurys lower, oil slightly higher, gold little changedOvernight Action: BP Net Profit Rises; S&P Changes Japan Outlook to Negative;Watch for: Fed rate decision and press conference,  earnings from Ebay, Starbucks, Boeing, ConocoPhillipsThe Breakfast BriefingToday, all eyes will go to the Bearded One.Federal Reserve Chairman Ben Bernanke will face the scribes in a first-ever press conference at 2:15 p.m. EDT. The Fed says the press conference is aimed at increasing transparency. It?s more likely to be a tour de force in sleep-inducing obfuscation.The Federal Open Market Committee, the Fed?s policy group, will issue its statement at 1230 p.m. EDT, ahead of Big Ben?s 2:15 p.m. EDT date with the press. It is difficult to imagine that Big Ben will break new ground at the microphone, but there?s always hope. Jean-Claude Trichet, head of the European Central Bank, used a press briefing to signal that the ECB planned to raise rates this month, which it did early this month. (The ECB, like other central banks, has held press briefings for years.)The dollar?s recent weakness ? the dollar index is at a three-year low and the euro is at a fresh 52-week high ? underscores the belief that the Fed is in no rush to tighten its extraordinarily loose monetary policy. Our friends at Real Time Economics offer a nifty primer on how to interpret the words and phrases of Big Ben. (The over/under betting line for number of chuckles Big Ben gets: three.)The Fed, in its statement, is expected to say it will finish its $600 billion quantitative easing program (QE2) on schedule in June. It is also not expected to raise too many alarms about looming interest-rate moves. The Fed-funds futures sees only a 26% chance that the Fed will raise rates to 0.5% by next February.As investors fidget about what the Bearded One might say, earnings will come in full force once again.
